. @Swizec 
Check out my project, [coffeeshop.js](https://github.com/daxxog/coffeeshop.js). I created something called "hybrid rendering" which does just this with node-static.

Basically it's a [async](https://github.com/caolan/async) loop that runs a user defined function that tells it if it needs to render a file. If it responds true, the async loop runs another function that renders the file. It then sleeps for a little bit and checks again.

Whats nice about my solution is you can use it for just about anything. A [mustache](http://mustache.github.com/) template, a JSON file that gets updated with a database, a [less](https://github.com/cloudhead/less.js) template, a JavaScript source that needs to be [uglified](https://github.com/mishoo/UglifyJS2)... etc.

My project includes an example that connects to [MongoDB](https://github.com/mongodb/node-mongodb-native), renders a mustache template, less template, and JavaScript with [UglifyJS](https://github.com/mishoo/UglifyJS2).
. I think it should be a separate project. One thing we could add is a function that receives the file data as input and spits out some output. That way it would be possible to create external plugins for this type of stuff. Just a thought.
