mrozbarry:
Just to update, I sorted out that my code was only working for 200s (when the file just existed), and after fiddling a bit, this ended up working:

```
  public.serve(request, response, function(error, res) {
    if (error) {
      console.error('Could not serve ', request.url, error.message);
      if ([404, 500].indexOf(error.status) >= 0) {
        public.serveFile('index.html', 404, {}, request, response);
      }
    }
```

I also went into index.html, and added this to the head:

```
<base href="/" />
```

This is now working and all my assets are loading.

What was happening before was that my page actually loaded fine, but when it hit a 404, it would send either no bytes for nodia.js (since /my/pushState/url/nodia.js didn't exist), or the 404 tried to force-load my index.html (which obviously isn't javascript).

**Edit:** I should note that I was purposefully avoiding express, since it adds a lot of bulk and features that I wasn't ever going to use (like routing).  My project did start off with express, though, but it was making less and less sense to use it.  Now, if you're building out a restful backend or something, it might be worth it, but I'm doing my own restful stuff via websockets, so again, it was something I didn't need express for.

Sorry that felt like a rant, I've just had a lot of people to tell me to use express and when I saw how unnecessary it was, it sort of bothered me that people were more willing to add bulk to their app than to solve smaller problems on their own.
